article.description: Connecticut beat the Houston Comets 65-58 in a WNBA game Saturday.
article.headline: Sun benefit from Swoopes' second-half absence
article.linkText: Sun eclipse Comets again, helped by Swoopes' injury
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- With their home court smack in the
middle of a sprawling, glitzy casino, the Connecticut Sun want
their opponents to enjoy the surroundings, but not the game.

"They can come and shop and everything. We want to establish
this as a place where people don't want to come to play," forward
Rebecca Lobo said Saturday night after Connecticut's 65-58 victory
over the Houston Comets.

Shannon Johnson scored 21 points and had eight assists for
Connecticut (3-2), which also beat the slumping Comets 91-83 in
Houston on May 30. The victory was the Sun's first at home.

"That felt like a playoff game emotionally," Sun coach Mike
Thibault said. "There was a sense of urgency to win at home and
get people excited about coming to see us play."

The Comets (3-4), who have lost four of their last five, were
without two-time league MVP Sheryl Swoopes for most of the game
after she sprained her right ankle in the closing minutes of the
first half.

Nykesha Sales added 14 points, seven rebounds and four steals
for Connecticut.

Tina Thompson led the Comets (3-4) with 25 points, including
eight in a 15-2 spurt after Swoopes went out with 5:10 left in the
first half.

Swoopes was hurt while battling the Sales for a loose ball under
the Comets' basket. As Swoopes jumped for the ball, Sales fell and
Swoopes landed awkwardly on her. Swoopes lay there for several
moments before being helped off the court. Swoopes finished with
five points and three rebounds in 11 minutes of play.

"It's especially tough when you lose your best player," Comets
guard Janeth Arcain said. "We have to find a way to make
improvements when we get back home."

Swoopes' injury was diagnosed as a moderate sprain. She's
scheduled to undergo further tests when the team returns to Houston on Sunday morning.

The Comets led 38-32 at the half and dominated the boards early,
holding a 20-10 rebounding edge at the break. The Sun were playing
without Wendy Palmer, their second-leading rebounder, who suffered
a neck injury in last week's win at San Antonio.

Thibault said he let his team have it in the locker room at
halftime, underscoring the disparity on the boards, and challenged
the Sun to match Houston's physical play.

He wasn't disappointed.

The Sun outrebounded Houston 19-15 in the second period and got
an emotional lift from bench players Debbie Black, Jessie Hicks and
Brooke Wycoff.

"We accepted the challenge a whole lot better," Thibault said.
"We held them to 20 points and contested every shot."

Black, the feisty 5-foot-3 guard, was the emotional spark for
the Sun in the second half. She had three of her four steals and
all of her eight points in the period.

She also was called for a technical with 11:36 left when she
tangled with Dominique Canty as they scrambled for a ball. Black
sailed out of bounds and landed halfway beneath the press table.
Their legs locked up as Canty ran by and Black kicked at her. She
said Canty kicked her first, but the referee didn't see it that
way.

"The second one's always the one that gets caught," Black
said.

Thompson hit the technical free throw to tie the game at 43-all.
Canty made one of her two free throws to put the Comets up by a
point.

But Black came right back and hit a 16-foot jumper to put the
Sun up for good at 45-44 and kick off a 6-0 run.

"When you play with Debbie Black, if you're not playing hard
then something's missing," Thibault said. "She makes you play
hard and people feed off that energy."

The Comets closed to 59-55 on Arcain's jumper with 1:30 left.
But Hicks hit a wide-open shot down low for the Sun with 1:08 to
play and Connecticut was 4-of-4 from the free-throw line to ice the
game.

"That's how you win championships," Thibault said. "L.A. and
Houston, they're focused on winning championships. That's where I
want our team to be."
